The large value of the first principal component in the fingers suggests that a simple design can easily take advantage of the demonstrated synergies. Conversely, the roughly even values of the first two principal components in the thumb indicate that neither is dominant, making significantly more complex mechanisms necessary for implementation. Thus it was decided to only implement the synergistic design on the fingers, leaving improvements to the actuation of the thumb for later work. The principal direction of variation as determined by the PCA analysis is applied to the

